---
import ContentLayout from '../../layouts/ContentLayout.astro';
export const prerender = true;

const faqItems = [
  {
    q: "Does cold email still work for coffee wholesale?",
    a: "Yes, when it is done with research and restraint. Café owners and buyers read email, and most specialty roasters either never send cold outreach or send generic blasts that get ignored. A short, specific, well-timed email that shows you actually looked at the café and offers a clear, low-friction next step still gets responses. The roasters who complain that cold email is dead are usually the ones sending the same template to two hundred addresses at once."
  },
  {
    q: "What is a good subject line for a coffee wholesale email?",
    a: "Keep it short, specific, and free of sales language. Reference the café by name or mention something concrete: 'Coffee for [Café Name]' or 'Sample for your bar program' works better than 'Partner with our award-winning roastery.' The job of the subject line is to earn the open, not to make the pitch. Lowercase, plain phrasing that looks like a note from a real person tends to outperform polished marketing copy."
  },
  {
    q: "How long should a cold wholesale email be?",
    a: "Under 120 words. Buyers scan on their phones between tasks, so a long email reads as work and gets postponed into oblivion. Lead with why you are writing to them specifically, say one concrete thing about your coffee, make a single easy ask (usually a free sample), and stop. If they are interested, the details come in the reply. The first email only has to earn the next message, not close the account."
  },
  {
    q: "How many follow-ups should a cold email sequence have?",
    a: "Plan for four to six touches over three to four weeks, each adding something new rather than just checking in. Most closed wholesale deals take five or more touches, but most roasters quit after one. Space your follow-ups a few business days apart, change the angle each time, and always give the buyer a reason to read beyond the ask. A structured sequence is what separates roasters who close consistently from ones who give up early."
  },
  {
    q: "Is cold emailing cafés legal under CAN-SPAM?",
    a: "Cold B2B email is legal in the United States under the CAN-SPAM Act as long as you follow the rules: use accurate from and subject lines, identify the message honestly, include a valid physical mailing address, and give recipients a clear way to opt out that you honor promptly. You do not need prior consent to send a first commercial email to a business contact, but you must stop if they ask. Check local rules if you are emailing buyers outside the US."
  }
];

